## Overview

Devscribe supports two approaches for creating API documentation: **OpenAPI-based** (automatic generation from specification) and **manual** (custom MDX with API components). Choose OpenAPI for standard REST APIs with existing specifications, or manual mode for custom documentation needs.

<Callout type="tip">
OpenAPI mode is recommended for most use cases. It automatically generates complete API documentation from your specification, eliminating manual maintenance and ensuring accuracy.
</Callout>

---

## OpenAPI Documentation

### How it works

OpenAPI mode reads your OpenAPI specification file and automatically generates complete API documentation including parameters, request bodies, responses, code examples, and an interactive playground.

**Location of specification**: `src/app/(pages)/openapi.json`

### Frontmatter configuration

<ParameterField name="title" type="string" required>
The endpoint name displayed as the page heading.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="description" type="string">
Brief description of what the endpoint does. Appears below the title and in SEO metadata.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="openapi" type="string" required>
Triggers OpenAPI mode. Format: `METHOD /path` (e.g., `GET /users/{id}`). Must match an operation defined in your OpenAPI specification.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="icon" type="string">
Icon name from Lucide icons library. Displays in navigation sidebar.
</ParameterField>

### Creating an OpenAPI endpoint page

<Steps>
<Step title="Define endpoint in OpenAPI specification">

Add your endpoint to `src/app/(pages)/openapi.json`:

<CodeSnippet language="json" title="openapi.json" showLineNumbers={true}>
{`{
  "openapi": "3.0.0",
  "info": {
    "title": "Your API",
    "version": "1.0.0"
  },
  "paths": {
    "/users/{id}": {
      "get": {
        "summary": "Get User",
        "description": "Retrieve a user by their unique identifier",
        "parameters": [
          {
            "name": "id",
            "in": "path",
            "required": true,
            "schema": { "type": "string" },
            "description": "Unique user identifier"
          }
        ],
        "responses": {
          "200": {
            "description": "User retrieved successfully",
            "content": {
              "application/json": {
                "schema": {
                  "$ref": "#/components/schemas/User"
                }
              }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  "components": {
    "schemas": {
      "User": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "id": { "type": "string" },
          "email": { "type": "string" },
          "name": { "type": "string" }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}`}
</CodeSnippet>
</Step>

<Step title="Create MDX file">

Create a new `.mdx` file in your API reference directory (e.g., `src/app/(pages)/api-reference/users/get-user.mdx`):

<CodeSnippet language="yaml" title="get-user.mdx">
{`---
title: Get User
description: Retrieve a user by their unique identifier
openapi: GET /users/{id}
icon: user
---`}
</CodeSnippet>

<Callout type="info">
No body content is required. All documentation is automatically generated from your OpenAPI specification.
</Callout>
</Step>

<Step title="Add to navigation">

Register the page in `src/app/(pages)/docs.json`:

<CodeSnippet language="json" title="docs.json">
{`{
  "navigation": {
    "tabs": [
      {
        "tab": "API Reference",
        "groups": [
          {
            "group": "Users",
            "pages": [
              "api-reference/users/get-user"
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}`}
</CodeSnippet>
</Step>
</Steps>

### Auto-generated features

OpenAPI mode automatically generates:

- **Method badge** with color coding (GET=green, POST=blue, PUT=yellow, DELETE=red, PATCH=orange)
- **Authentication requirements** from security schemes
- **Path parameters** with types, descriptions, and constraints
- **Query parameters** with defaults and examples
- **Request body schema** with nested properties
- **Response schemas** for all status codes
- **cURL examples** with proper authentication
- **Response examples** with realistic JSON
- **Interactive playground** with "Try it" button

### Supported OpenAPI features

<AccordionGroup>
<Accordion title="Parameters">
- Path parameters (`in: path`)
- Query parameters (`in: query`)
- Header parameters (`in: header`)
- Cookie parameters (`in: cookie`)
- Required/optional indicators
- Default values
- Enums and constraints
- Deprecated parameters
</Accordion>

<Accordion title="Request bodies">
- JSON schema definitions
- Multiple content types (`application/json`, `multipart/form-data`, etc.)
- Required properties
- Nested objects with `$ref`
- Arrays and collections
- Schema composition (`allOf`, `oneOf`, `anyOf`)
</Accordion>

<Accordion title="Responses">
- Multiple status codes (200, 400, 404, etc.)
- Response schema definitions
- Nested response objects
- `$ref` resolution for reusable schemas
- Response examples
- Content type specifications
</Accordion>

<Accordion title="Security">
- Bearer token authentication
- API key authentication (header, query, cookie)
- OAuth2 flows
- Multiple security schemes
- Per-operation security overrides
</Accordion>
</AccordionGroup>

### OpenAPI specification structure

Your `openapi.json` must follow OpenAPI 3.x specification:

<CodeSnippet language="json" title="openapi.json">
{`{
  "openapi": "3.0.0",
  "info": {
    "title": "API Name",
    "description": "API description",
    "version": "1.0.0"
  },
  "servers": [
    {
      "url": "https://api.example.com",
      "description": "Production server"
    }
  ],
  "security": [
    {
      "bearerAuth": []
    }
  ],
  "paths": {
    "/endpoint": {
      "get": {
        "summary": "Short summary",
        "description": "Detailed description",
        "parameters": [],
        "requestBody": {},
        "responses": {}
      }
    }
  },
  "components": {
    "schemas": {},
    "securitySchemes": {
      "bearerAuth": {
        "type": "http",
        "scheme": "bearer"
      }
    }
  }
}`}
</CodeSnippet>

<Callout type="warning">
The `openapi` frontmatter value must exactly match a path and method defined in your specification. Case-sensitive matching: `GET /users/{id}` must match `paths["/users/{id}"].get` in your spec.
</Callout>

