## Manual API Documentation

### When to use manual mode

Use manual API documentation when:

- You need custom content beyond standard API reference
- Your API doesn't follow REST conventions
- You want complete control over layout and presentation
- You're documenting webhooks, events, or non-HTTP protocols
- You need to mix API reference with conceptual content

### Frontmatter configuration

<ParameterField name="title" type="string" required>
The endpoint name displayed as the page heading.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="description" type="string">
Brief description of what the endpoint does.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="api" type="string" required>
Triggers manual API mode. Format: `METHOD /path` (e.g., `POST /documents`).
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="num" type="integer">
Number of code blocks toextract to the right column. Set to `2` to move the first two code blocks from the main content to the right sidebar.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="icon" type="string">
Icon name from Lucide icons library.
</ParameterField>

### Creating a manual API page

<CodeSnippet language="yaml" title="create-document.mdx">
{`---
title: Create Document
description: Create a new document in your workspace
api: POST /documents
num: 2
icon: file-plus
---

Create a new document by providing content and metadata. Returns the created document with a unique identifier.

### Authorization

<ParameterField name="Authorization" type="string" required>
Bearer token for authentication. Format: \`Bearer YOUR_API_KEY\`
</ParameterField>

### Body Parameters

<ParameterField name="title" type="string" required>
Document title. Maximum 200 characters.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="content" type="string" required>
Document content in markdown format.
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="tags" type="array">
Optional tags for categorization. Array of strings.
</ParameterField>

### Responses

<APIResponse status="201" description="Document created successfully" contentType="application/json" defaultOpen>
  <APIResponseField name="id" type="string" description="Unique document identifier" />
  <APIResponseField name="title" type="string" description="Document title" />
  <APIResponseField name="created_at" type="string" description="ISO 8601 timestamp" />
</APIResponse>

<APIResponse status="400" description="Invalid request" contentType="application/json">
  <APIResponseField name="error" type="string" description="Error message" />
</APIResponse>

<CodeGroup>
  <CodeSnippet language="bash" title="cURL">
  {\`curl -X POST https://api.example.com/documents \\
  -H 'Authorization: Bearer YOUR_API_KEY' \\
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \\
  -d '{
    "title": "Getting Started",
    "content": "# Welcome\\nThis is my first document.",
    "tags": ["guide", "onboarding"]
  }'\`}
  </CodeSnippet>
  
  <CodeSnippet language="javascript" title="JavaScript">
  {\`const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/documents', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: {
      'Authorization': 'Bearer YOUR_API_KEY',
      'Content-Type': 'application/json'
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      title: 'Getting Started',
      content: '# Welcome\\nThis is my first document.',
      tags: ['guide', 'onboarding']
    })
  });
  
  const data = await response.json();\`}
  </CodeSnippet>
</CodeGroup>

<CodeGroup>
  <CodeSnippet language="json" title="201 Response">
  {\`{
    "id": "doc_abc123",
    "title": "Getting Started",
    "content": "# Welcome\\nThis is my first document.",
    "tags": ["guide", "onboarding"],
    "created_at": "2024-01-15T10:30:00Z",
    "updated_at": "2024-01-15T10:30:00Z"
  }\`}
  </CodeSnippet>
</CodeGroup>`}
</CodeSnippet>

### API documentation components

#### ParameterField

Document request parameters with type information and constraints:

<CodeSnippet language="jsx">
{`<ParameterField 
  name="user_id" 
  type="string" 
  required
  default="123"
  example="usr_abc123"
  enum={["active", "inactive"]}
  deprecated
>
  User's unique identifier. Must be a valid UUID v4 format.
</ParameterField>`}
</CodeSnippet>

**Props:**

<ParameterField name="name" type="string" required>
Parameter name
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="type" type="string" required>
Data type (e.g., `string`, `integer`, `boolean`, `array`, `object`)
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="required" type="boolean">
Displays "required" badge when present
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="default" type="string">
Default value if parameter is omitted
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="example" type="string">
Example value
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="enum" type="array">
Array of allowed values
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="deprecated" type="boolean">
Marks parameter as deprecated
</ParameterField>

#### APIResponse

Document response structures by status code:

<CodeSnippet language="jsx">
{`<APIResponse 
  status="200" 
  description="Success response" 
  contentType="application/json"
  defaultOpen
>
  <APIResponseField 
    name="id" 
    type="string" 
    description="Resource identifier" 
  />
  <APIResponseField 
    name="email" 
    type="string" 
    description="User email address" 
  />
</APIResponse>`}
</CodeSnippet>

**Props:**

<ParameterField name="status" type="string" required>
HTTP status code (e.g., `200`, `400`, `404`)
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="description" type="string">
Response description
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="contentType" type="string">
Content type (e.g., `application/json`)
</ParameterField>

<ParameterField name="defaultOpen" type="boolean">
Response section expanded by default
</ParameterField>

#### Nested response fields

Use `Expand` component for nested object properties:

<CodeSnippet language="jsx">
{`<APIResponse status="200" description="User with profile" contentType="application/json">
  <APIResponseField name="user" type="object" description="User object">
    <Expand title="User properties">
      <APIResponseField name="id" type="string" description="User ID" />
      <APIResponseField name="profile" type="object" description="Profile data">
        <Expand title="Profile properties">
          <APIResponseField name="avatar_url" type="string" description="Profile picture URL" />
          <APIResponseField name="bio" type="string" description="User biography" />
        </Expand>
      </APIResponseField>
    </Expand>
  </APIResponseField>
</APIResponse>`}
</CodeSnippet>

### Two-column layout with num

The `num` frontmatter field controls code block extraction to the right column:

<CodeSnippet language="yaml">
{`---
title: Create Document
api: POST /documents
num: 2
---`}
</CodeSnippet>

With `num: 2`, the first two `<CodeGroup>` blocks in your MDX content are moved to the right sidebar, creating a classic API docs layout with description on the left and code examples on the right.

<Callout type="tip">
Set `num` equal to the number of `<CodeGroup>` blocks containing request and response examples to achieve the standard two-column API reference layout.
</Callout>

