## Best Practices

### OpenAPI specifications

<Callout type="tip">
Keep your OpenAPI specification as the single source of truth. Update the spec first, then regenerate documentation automatically.
</Callout>

- Use `$ref` to reuse common schemas across endpoints
- Define reusable components in `components.schemas`
- Include realistic examples in schema definitions
- Document all possible response status codes
- Use clear, descriptive operation summaries
- Add detailed descriptions for complex parameters
- Define security schemes at the specification level
- Use tags to group related operations

### Manual API documentation

- Maintain consistent parameter ordering: path, query, headers, body
- Always document authentication requirements
- Include both success and error responses
- Provide request examples in multiple languages
- Show realistic response examples with actual data
- Document rate limits and pagination
- Explain error codes and handling
- Include examples for edge cases

### Code examples

<Callout type="warning">
Never include real API keys, tokens, or sensitive credentials in code examples. Use placeholder values like `YOUR_API_KEY`.
</Callout>

- Provide cURL examples for every endpoint
- Include examples in popular languages (JavaScript, Python, etc.)
- Show complete, runnable code that users can copy
- Include proper error handling in code examples
- Use realistic data instead of placeholders like `foo`, `bar`
- Add comments explaining complex parameters

### Content organization

- Group related endpoints together in navigation
- Place authentication documentation before endpoint reference
- Order endpoints by common workflows (list, create, get, update, delete)
- Use consistent naming across similar endpoints
- Add an API introduction page explaining base URLs, authentication, and common patterns

